<paper id="1967390724"><title>Iteration theories of synchronization trees</title><year>1993</year><authors><author org="Stevens Institute of Technology Castle Point" id="2164902142">Stephen L. Bloom</author><author org="A. József University" id="2021889967">Zoltán Ésik</author><author org="Techn. Univ. München" id="2721975938">Dirk Taubner</author></authors><n_citation>30</n_citation><doc_type>Journal</doc_type><references><reference>74837410</reference><reference>1503973138</reference><reference>1523024696</reference><reference>1547562281</reference><reference>1765032207</reference><reference>1987000283</reference><reference>2000059452</reference><reference>2029312575</reference><reference>2037767787</reference><reference>2061786858</reference><reference>2082206335</reference><reference>2085922276</reference><reference>2087393138</reference><reference>2088049948</reference><reference>2140920629</reference><reference>2158942489</reference><reference>2169869634</reference></references><venue id="59933527" type="J">Information &amp; Computation</venue><doi>10.1006/inco.1993.1001</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.46785">Discrete mathematics</keyword><keyword weight="0.49558">Synchronization</keyword><keyword weight="0.45974">Combinatorics</keyword><keyword weight="0.51677">Algebraic theory</keyword><keyword weight="0.56065">Bisimulation</keyword><keyword weight="0.46894">Idempotence</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Bisimulation equivalence</keyword><keyword weight="0.43501">Mathematics</keyword></keywords><publisher>Academic Press, Inc.</publisher><abstract>Abstract Synchronization trees are shown to form an iteration theory in a natural way. The class of grove theories is introduced. The regular synchronization trees are shown to be the free theories in the subclass of synchronization theories. Moreover. the bisimulation equivalence classes of regular synchronization trees are shown to be the free synchronization theories satisfying an "infinite" idempotency law.</abstr